---
// odal-node.io — home page.
// Section order and copy per docs/WEB_CONTENT_STRATEGY.md §4.
// Terminology and claims rules: see §7 (no capability-tier language, no claims
// ahead of shipped code, "proof-bound" never "no-touch").
import DeadlineCards from "../components/DeadlineCards.astro";
import Hero from "../components/Hero.astro";
import Section from "../components/Section.astro";
import StandardsRow from "../components/StandardsRow.astro";
import Base from "../layouts/Base.astro";

const title = "Odal Node — EU Digital Product Passport Infrastructure | ESPR Compliance";
const description =
  "Open-source infrastructure for EU Digital Product Passports (DPP) under ESPR. Self-hosted, sovereign compliance — your product data is validated and signed with your keys. Battery, textile, and electronics passports.";

// Page-specific structured data.
const softwareAppLd = {
  "@context": "https://schema.org",
  "@type": "SoftwareApplication",
  name: "Odal Node",
  applicationCategory: "BusinessApplication",
  operatingSystem: "Linux, Docker",
  description:
    "Self-hosted infrastructure for EU Digital Product Passports (DPP) under the Ecodesign for Sustainable Products Regulation (ESPR). Validates product data against sector schemas, signs with your keys, and publishes verifiable passports via GS1 Digital Link.",
  url: "https://odal-node.io",
  offers: {
    "@type": "Offer",
    price: "0",
    priceCurrency: "EUR",
    description: "Open-core: dpp-core is Apache-2.0; dpp-engine is BSL-1.1 with free self-host grant.",
  },
  license: "https://opensource.org/licenses/Apache-2.0",
  codeRepository: "https://github.com/odal-node/dpp-core",
};

// The end-to-end process as one timeline. On the landing the underlying
// services (integrator, validation, vault + in-process signing, resolver) are
// deliberately merged into a single flow; the docs keep them as separate pages.
const steps = [
  { label: "Import", body: "Product data from CSV, Excel, or your ERP into your own node." },
  { label: "Validate", body: "Against versioned sector schemas tracking the regulation, locally." },
  { label: "Sign", body: "With your own key, generated and held on your infrastructure." },
  { label: "Publish", body: "Only the signed passport becomes resolvable, via QR and GS1 Digital Link." },
];
---

<Base title={title} description={description} jsonLd={[softwareAppLd]}>
  <Hero
    eyebrow="EU Digital Product Passports"
    status
    title="Signed by you. Verified by anyone."
    subtitle="Odal Node is sovereign infrastructure for EU Digital Product Passports. Your product data is validated and signed on your infrastructure, with your keys — the raw import files are discarded, the signed passport is stored and served. Anyone can verify it."
    primaryHref="https://docs.odal-node.io/quick-start"
    primaryLabel="Self-host now"
    secondaryHref="https://docs.odal-node.io"
    secondaryLabel="Read the docs"
  />

  <Section eyebrow="Why now" title="The deadlines are set. The infrastructure mostly isn't." wide>
    <p>
      Compliance arrives sector by sector, date by date — not "everything by 2027."
      Three dated obligations are already in law:
    </p>
    <div class="not-prose mt-8">
      <DeadlineCards />
    </div>
    <p class="mt-8">
      The question is whether the infrastructure you adopt now still fits the next
      sector's act. Odal Node is built so that it does: new sectors arrive as schema
      and plugin updates, not as new systems.
    </p>
  </Section>

  <Section eyebrow="How it works" title="Proof-bound: the data stays yours. Every field it publishes is bound to a proof." tone="tinted">
    <p>
      Manufacturers keep trade secrets. Regulators and customers need data they can
      trust. A proof-bound architecture serves both without asking either to
      compromise: the raw import files are read once and discarded, while the signed
      passport they produce — carrying the full product data, every field bound to a
      proof — is what the node stores and serves, released to each audience by access
      tier.
    </p>
    <div class="not-prose my-6">
      <ol class="grid grid-cols-1 gap-8 md:grid-cols-4 md:gap-4">
        {steps.map((s, i) => (
          <li>
            <div class="flex items-center">
              <span class="flex h-10 w-10 shrink-0 items-center justify-center rounded-full border-2 border-primary-500 bg-neutral-0 text-sm font-semibold text-primary-700">
                {i + 1}
              </span>
              {i < steps.length - 1 && (
                <span class="ml-3 hidden h-0.5 flex-1 bg-primary-200 md:block" aria-hidden="true"></span>
              )}
            </div>
            <h3 class="mb-1 mt-4 text-base font-semibold text-neutral-900">{s.label}</h3>
            <p class="m-0 text-sm leading-body text-neutral-600">{s.body}</p>
          </li>
        ))}
      </ol>
    </div>
    <p>
      Anyone verifies the signature against your public DID document — without Odal in
      the loop. Public fields are readable by all; restricted tiers — for repairers,
      recyclers, and market-surveillance authorities — are released only against a
      verified credential. What the node stores: the signed passport with every tier,
      the audit trail, the signature. What it never stores: raw import files,
      supply-chain detail beyond passport content, or your private keys.
    </p>
  </Section>

  <Section eyebrow="What you get" title="Built for the compliance officer and the engineer at the same desk." wide>
    <div class="not-prose grid gap-6 md:grid-cols-2 lg:grid-cols-3">
      {[
        {
          k: "Proof-bound by architecture",
          v: "The raw import files are discarded after signing; the signed passport is what's stored and served. A property of the software, not a policy promise.",
        },
        {
          k: "Standards-native",
          v: "GS1 Digital Link 1.2 resolution, W3C VC 2.0 credentials, did:web identity, AAS submodel export.",
        },
        {
          k: "Sandboxed sector plugins",
          v: "Each sector's compliance logic runs in an isolated sandbox. New regulations land as plugins, not rewrites.",
        },
        {
          k: "Honest open-core",
          v: "dpp-core (the regulatory standard in Rust) is Apache-2.0, full capability, forever. dpp-engine is BSL-1.1 with a real self-host grant — production self-hosting is free.",
        },
        {
          k: "No vendor lock-in",
          v: "The node is a single, self-contained service. You can run it on your own infrastructure, or on a cloud you control.",
        },
        {
          k: "Self-host in minutes",
          v: "One compose file. No licence keys, no passport caps. Ever.",
        },
      ].map((f) => (
        <article class="rounded-md border border-neutral-200 bg-neutral-0 p-6 transition-colors hover:border-primary-300">
          <h3 class="mb-2 mt-0 text-base font-semibold text-neutral-900">{f.k}</h3>
          <p class="m-0 text-sm leading-body text-neutral-600">{f.v}</p>
        </article>
      ))}
    </div>
  </Section>


  <Section eyebrow="Data and trust" title="What Odal Node can and cannot see." tone="tinted" wide>
    <p>
      Proof-bound is not a promise about our conduct; it is a property of the
      software. The node reads your import files once and discards them — so the raw
      production data behind a passport is never ours to access, by construction.
      Stated precisely:
    </p>
    <div class="not-prose mt-8 grid gap-6 md:grid-cols-3">
      <div class="rounded-md border border-neutral-200 bg-neutral-0 p-6">
        <h3 class="mb-2 mt-0 text-sm font-semibold uppercase tracking-wide text-primary-700">We can see</h3>
        <p class="m-0 text-sm leading-body text-neutral-600">
          The signed passport you publish to a resolver we operate, and the
          metadata required to serve it.
        </p>
      </div>
      <div class="rounded-md border border-neutral-200 bg-neutral-0 p-6">
        <h3 class="mb-2 mt-0 text-sm font-semibold uppercase tracking-wide text-primary-700">We cannot see</h3>
        <p class="m-0 text-sm leading-body text-neutral-600">
          Your private keys (held in-process on your infrastructure), your raw
          production data, your supply-chain detail.
        </p>
      </div>
      <div class="rounded-md border border-neutral-200 bg-neutral-0 p-6">
        <h3 class="mb-2 mt-0 text-sm font-semibold uppercase tracking-wide text-primary-700">We could see but do not</h3>
        <p class="m-0 text-sm leading-body text-neutral-600">
          The contents of your import files, which the node discards after
          validation.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
    <p class="mt-8 text-sm">
      <!-- <a href="/trust" class="font-medium">Read the full breakdown →</a> -->
    </p>
  </Section>

  <!-- <GetStarted /> -->

  <Section eyebrow="Standards" title="Built on the standards the regulation itself cites." tone="muted" wide>
    <div class="not-prose mt-2">
      <StandardsRow />
    </div>
  </Section>
</Base>
